  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms and principles:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Provide standardized frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute cross-border financial crimes\n- Sharing evidence and legal resources\n- Extradition agreements for money laundering suspects\n\n3. Regulatory Standards\n- Establish common reporting requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Uniform guidelines for financial institutions\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- International sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Monitoring financial systems globally\n- Pressuring countries to strengthen anti-money laundering regulations\n\n5. Information Sharing\n- International banking networks\n- Intelligence exchange between financial intelligence units\n- Coordinated tracking of suspicious financial movements\n\n6. Enforcement Cooperation\n- Joint investigations\n- Coordinated legal actions\n- Shared technological resources for financial crime detection\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering across national boundaries.",
